b'' b'stephen a. creps writes to all:' b'' b'[...]' b'' b'sac also, we know that' b'sac the bible says that _everyone_ must be baptized to enter heaven.' b'' b'where exactly does it say that?' b'' b'sac _everyone_ includes infants, unless there is other scripture to the' b'sac contrary, i.e. an exception. since there is no exception listed in the' b'sac bible, we must assume (to be on the safe side) that the bible means what' b'sac it says, that _everyone_ must be baptized to enter heaven.' b'' b'i think we do see an exception in the case of cornelius and his' b'household, mentioned in acts. of course, they were baptised, but only' b'after "god showed that he accepted them by giving them the holy' b'spirit". this means they were already acceptable to god before their' b'baptism, and had they suddenly died they would have gone to heaven.' b'' b'in case that seems far-fetched an ancestor of mine was a missionary' b'who worked among the hereros in namibia. some of the tribesmen were' b'jealous of christianity, and they poisoned the first convert before he' b"could be baptised. surely he still went to heaven? i'm inclined to" b'agree with a comment recorded at the time: "it is not the neglect of' b'baptism, but its contempt, that condemns."' b'' b'mike' b'--' b'via: the catalyst bbs in port elizabeth, south africa.' b'(catpe.alt.za) v32bis hst.' 